18. sumptuosa hostia : (1) if these words are, as the metre seems to show, in the ablative, the line is parenthetical, blandior referring to manus in v. 17 ; “ (thy hand) no more persuasive with (ablative of instrument) a costly sacrifice,” i.e. ‘⁶ that would not be more persuasive were it to offer a costly sacrifice.’‘ (2) But some scholars, disliking the harsh parenthesis, hold that sumptuosa hostia may be nominative, the short a at the end of sumptuosa forming a long syllable with the following bl. If this is so, the comma after hostia must be removed, and hostia becomes the subject of mollivit : ‘⁶ a costly sacrifice has not more persuasively appeased the estranged household gods than holy meal,’' etc„ farre being ablative of the standard of comparison. Against this rendering there is not only the metrical difficulty, but also the awkwardness of the two adjectives sumptuosa and blandior applied to one substantive.
